  "footnotes": [
    "Roman Dacia province (106–271 CE): Established by Trajan after two Dacian wars; the region became heavily Romanised, giving rise to the Romanian people and language.",
    "Phanariot governors: Greek families from the Phanar district of Constantinople appointed by the Ottoman sultan to govern Wallachia (from 1716) and Moldavia (from 1711); marked by corruption and heavy tribute.",
    "United Principalities (1859): Alexandru Ioan Cuza was elected ruler of both Wallachia and Moldavia, de facto unifying them; the union was formally recognised in 1861 as the Romanian Principality.",
    "Duchy of Bukovina (1775): The Habsburg Empire acquired northwestern Moldavia from the Ottoman Empire; it remained Austrian (later Austrian Küstenland) until 1918, when it joined Romania.",
    "Second Vienna Award (1940): Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy awarded northern Transylvania to Hungary; Romania recovered it after Soviet entry in 1944, confirmed by Paris Peace Treaty (1947).",
    "Moldavian ASSR (1924–1940): Soviet puppet 'Moldavian' entity created on the east bank of the Dniester (modern Transnistria) to assert Soviet claims to Bessarabia.",
    "Transnistria (1992–present): Breakaway territory east of the Dniester; defeated Moldova in a brief 1992 war; Russian 14th Army remains; unrecognised by any UN member state."
  ]
